the compiler for a language whose source is human text, written as a module named engine that a separate repl imports whole, so it exposes ROOT (the directory the module sits in), LANG, PROGS, CACHE and BUILD beneath it, MODEL_ID, the exception Malformed, the class Node, and the functions lang_text, cached, call, call_json, serialize, generate, tally, caused_by, project, propose, lower, build and raises, and nothing else; a node is a .human file and the filesystem is the whole dag, so progs/sort.human is a root, progs/sort/1.human is its child and the directory of the same name is the parent, but every one of those relations is read off the path string alone and never off what happens to exist on disk, because a node names a place whether or not anyone has written it yet: Node('progs/sort/1/2') is constructed from that slash separated path, its file() is that path with .human under ROOT, its name() is the last segment, its level() is its depth below the root of its program so that a root is level 0, its parent() is the path with the last segment removed or None once only the program is left, its program() is the first two segments, its ancestors() run root first, its children() are the .human files in its directory ordered by their numeric names, its subtree() is itself followed by each child's subtree, its text() is the file stripped or empty when there is no file, and its intent() and assertions() split that text into the human sentence and the executable claims, a claim being a line beginning 'assert:', which is cut out of the intent and therefore out of every prompt the model ever sees, so that a claim can only be tested and never taught to; every model call goes to a single place, call(system, user), which is bedrock converse through boto3 at temperature zero with the region and the model id and the credentials taken from a .env beside the module, and call_json is the same call for the one stage that answers in json, retrying once with a sharper instruction before raising Malformed; every call is content addressed by cached(kind, key, fn), which hashes the kind of call, the model id, only the lang/ folder that kind reads and that kind's own system prompt together with the key, returns the json under that hash in CACHE if it is there and otherwise runs fn once and writes it, so an untouched program recompiles byte for byte, an edit to the codegen sheet does not invalidate lowering, and the second identical call costs nothing; serialize(root) lays the whole tree out one node per line, indented two spaces per level below the root, each line carrying the node's path and its intent, and it takes an optional path to drop, which removes that node and everything beneath it; generate(root) compiles the program in one call under the rules in lang/code, and generate(root, node, baseline) regenerates it under lang/code plus lang/reduce with that node dropped and the baseline handed back to the model as the thing it is correcting, and both of them read the answer as the last fenced python block whose fences each stand alone on their own line, because the compiler's own source carries fences inside its string literals and a fence found in the middle of a line is not a fence, and both send an unparseable answer back to the model with the parser's exact error appended, twice, before failing loudly, since nothing here may ever swallow a SyntaxError or accept an answer that carried no python at all; provenance is never claimed by the model but measured by deletion, so tally(code) is the multiset of every rstripped non-blank line, in which indentation is meaning and n copies of a line must survive n times, caused_by(root, node, baseline) returns two multisets and not their union, the lines the baseline had that the anchored regeneration lost, and the lines it invented that were never asked for, and project(code, caused), given the build and a map from each node's path to the multiset of lines that node caused, returns two maps keyed by line number as a string, the first giving every line the sorted list of paths that caused at least as many copies of it as the build contains, and the second holding only the lines that no path could claim outright though some path took a few of their copies away, which are ambiguous and are left unclaimed rather than guessed; a child earns its existence by the very measurement that audits it afterwards, so propose(node) asks lang/lower for the next level of human text with the ancestors and the settled siblings in the prompt and gets back leaf or a list of children, and lower(node) writes those children, deletes again every one whose removal changes no line of the build, renumbers the survivors and returns how many were proposed with the ones that lived, leaving nothing behind on disk if it raises; build(root) compiles the tree, writes it to BUILD/<name>/main.py, throws away any provenance map beside it that no longer matches, and returns that path with the code, because the map does not exist until ablation has been paid for; and raises(exc, fn, *args) reports whether a call raised what it was supposed to, so that a node's claims can demand an exception.
assert: Node('progs/sort/1/2').parent().path == 'progs/sort/1' and Node('progs/sort').parent() is None and Node('progs/sort/1/2').program().path == 'progs/sort' and Node('progs/sort/1/2').level() == 2 and Node('progs/sort').level() == 0 and Node('progs/sort/1').name() == '1'
assert: tally('a = 1\n\n  b = 2\n  b = 2\ntrail  \n') == {'a = 1': 1, '  b = 2': 2, 'trail': 1}
assert: (tally('keep\ngone\n') - tally('keep\n')) == {'gone': 1}
assert: project('x = 1\ny = 2\n', {'progs/p/1': tally('x = 1\n')}) == ({'1': ['progs/p/1'], '2': []}, {})
assert: project('x = 1\nx = 1\n', {'progs/p/1': tally('x = 1\n')}) == ({'1': [], '2': []}, {'1': ['progs/p/1'], '2': ['progs/p/1']})
assert: (lambda seen: cached('code', ['probe'], lambda: seen.append(1) or {'n': len(seen)}) == cached('code', ['probe'], lambda: seen.append(1) or {'n': len(seen)}))([])
assert: raises(ValueError, lambda: (_ for _ in ()).throw(ValueError())) and not raises(ValueError, lambda: None)
